  "body": "I have this code to create a `ref` and add it to the `state`:\r\n\r\n```jsx harmony\r\nconst [stateTitleBarRef, setStateTitleBarRef] = useState(null);\r\nconst titleBarRef = React.createRef();\r\n\r\nuseEffect(() => {\r\n  setStateTitleBarRef(titleBarRef);\r\n  console.log(stateTitleBarRef, titleBarRef);\r\n});\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe idea is that it adds the `ref` created above to the state once it's done rendering so subcomponents can use the ref (state updates triggering re-renders et all)\r\n\r\nI'm rendering a component with the `ref` like so:\r\n\r\n```jsx harmony\r\n<TitleBar containerRef={titleBarRef}/>\r\n```\r\n\r\n**What should happen** \r\n\r\n1. The main component renders\r\n2. `TitleBar` gets the `ref` setting the `current` property\r\n3. The main component updates state with the new `ref` containing `current`\r\n\r\n**What actually happens**\r\n\r\n1. The main component renders\r\n2. `TitleBar` gets the `ref` setting the `current` property\r\n3. The main component updates state with the new `ref`, `current` = `null`\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nI'm logging both in the effect code shown above.\r\n\r\n`console.log()` output:\r\n\r\n`{current: null} {current: div}`\r\n\r\nSo even after running the `setter` `current` is `null` but when I log the `ref` directly `current` is not `null`.\r\n\r\nAlso, if I don't add a `[]` as `useEffect()`'s second `parameter` it turns into an infinite loop.",
